{{About|Albanians that migrated in Greece after 1990|an overview of different communities of Albanian origin in Greece|Albanian communities in Greece}} {{Albanians}}
After the [[fall of communism]] throughout [[Eastern Europe]] in the late 1980s and early 1990s, a large number of economic refugees and immigrants from Greece's neighbouring countries, [[Albania]], [[Bulgaria]], the [[Republic of Macedonia]], [[Romania]], as well as from more distant countries such as [[Russia]], [[Ukraine]], [[Armenia]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], arrived in Greece, mostly as illegal immigrants, to seek employment.{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} The vast majority of Albanians in Greece is estimated to be between 60–65% of the total number of immigrants in Greece. According to official data (2008), there are 459,390<ref>[http://www.eliamep.gr/en/wp-content/uploads/2009/02/migration-and-migration-policy-in-greece-critical-review-and-policy-recommendations.pdf Migration and Migration Policy in Greece.]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Critical Review and Policy Recommendations. Anna Triandafyllidou. Hellenic Foundation for European and Foreign Policy (ELIAMEP)</ref> holders of Albanian citizenship in Greece.<ref>[http://www.migrantsingreece.org/transpartner/Tables.pdf Mediterranean Migration Observatory - Tables] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090325222928/http://www.migrantsingreece.org/transpartner/Tables.pdf |date=March 25, 2009 }}</ref>
They form the largest migrant group in Greece, but most of them don't want to be noticed as Albanian. Many Albanian newcomers change their [[Albanian name]] to [[Greek name|Greek]] ones and their religion from [[Islam]] to [[Greek Orthodox|Orthodoxy]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wienerzeitung.at/nachrichten/europa/europastaaten/562145_Griechenlands-verborgene-Albaner.html|title=Griechenlands verborgene Albaner|work=Wiener Zeitung|date=2013-07-16|author=Armand Feka|accessdate=2016-03-02|quotation=Er lächelt und antwortet in einwandfreiem Griechisch: ‚Ich bin eigentlich auch ein Albaner.' }}</ref> Even before emigration, more and more people in the south of Albania are pretending to be Greeks and even are changing their Muslim names to Greek ones in order to not being discriminated against in Greece. By this way, they hope to get a visa for Greece.<ref>{{cite book|author=Lars Brügger, Karl Kaser, Robert Pichler, Stephanie Schwander-Sievers|title=Umstrittene Identitäten. Grenzüberschreitungen zuhause und in der Fremde|work=Die weite Welt und das Dorf. Albanische Emigration am Ende des 20. Jahrhunderts = Zur Kunde Südosteuropas: Albanologische Studien|page=Bd. 3|publisher=Böhlau-Verlag|location=Vienna|date=2002|isbn=3-205-99413-2}}</ref> After migration to Greece, they get baptized and change the Albanian names in their passports to Greek ones.
